<br>
Entirely different from crashing a Pu-bearing probe into Europa. (Which I agree is careless, and probably asking for trouble from that treaty).<br>
 What he should remember about that Lunar mine picture, is what it's for:<br>
 The Space Colony studies were building a city for ~10,000 workers in space. They would then build more colonies and solar power satellites for supplying energy to Earth, and mne asteroids to supply materials to Earth &amp; space industries.<br>
 Note those 2 points: providing an endless supply of resources to Earth -<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>with no pollution on the Earth!</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> Absolutely limitless potential for growth, and supplying wealth &amp; goods to the people for a practially endless future.<br>
 (The entire Lunar mining effort, over a 20 year period, would produce one open pit mine about the size of a football field, maybe 3 meters deep. The mining effort would barely keep one tele-operated bulldozer occupied full-time.)<br>
 A further point: those asteroids he's worrying about &quot;polluting&quot; and mining are the same exact ones which pose the most danger of hitting Earth some day (The Earth-Crossers, with close to 1AU, 1year orbits)<br>
<br>
 Frankly, I think providing real solid hope for a limitless future of wealth for every human alive (thousands of times more people than today, if it happens that way) for an endless future is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> a little</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> more important than preserving the asteroids in their pristine primordial condition for posterity (with nobody out there to see the &quot;magnificent desolation&quot; of the natural condition).<br>
<br>
